{"title_page": "Blond Ambition World Tour Live", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Blond Ambition World Tour Live\n| type       = video\n| artist     = [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]\n| cover      = Madonna - Blond Ambition Live (Laser disc).png\n| alt        =\n| released   = December 13, 1990\n| recorded   = August 5, 1990\n| venue      = [[Stade Charles-Ehrmann|Stade de l'Ouest]]<br />([[Nice|Nice, France]])\n| studio     =\n| length     = 112 mins\n| label      = [[Pioneer Corporation|Pioneer Artists]]\n| director   = [[David Mallet (director)|David Mallet]]\n| producer   = Anthony Eaton\n| chronology = [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] video\n| prev_title = [[The Immaculate Collection (video)|The Immaculate Collection]]\n| prev_year  = 1990\n| next_title = [[The Girlie Show - Live Down Under]]\n| next_year  = 1994\n}}\n\n'''''Blond Ambition World Tour Live'''''  is a video album by American singer-songwriter [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] released exclusively on [[Laserdisc]] by [[Pioneer Corporation|Pioneer Artists]] on December 13, 1990. It contained the [[Blond Ambition World Tour]]'s final show, filmed at the [[Stade Charles-Ehrmann|Stade de l'Ouest]] in [[Nice|Nice, France]] on August 5, 1990. The concert had previously been broadcast on American network [[HBO]] as ''Live! Madonna: Blond Ambition World Tour 90'', and became one of its highest rated specials. The decision to release it exclusively on Laserdisc grew when Pioneer Artists signed up to sponsor the tour; the company also wanted to use Madonna to reach a new demographic and increase Laserdisc sales. It received positive reviews, with some critics saying it captured the concert better than the documentary ''[[Madonna: Truth or Dare]]'' and the HBO broadcast. At the [[34th Annual Grammy Awards]], it won for [[Grammy Award for Best Music Film|Best Music Video-Long Form]], becoming the first Grammy award Madonna received in her career.\n\n== Background ==\nThe Blond Ambition World Tour was Madonna's third concert tour. It supported her fourth studio album ''[[Like a Prayer (album)|Like a Prayer]]'' and the ''[[Dick Tracy (1990 film)|Dick Tracy]]'' soundtrack ''[[I'm Breathless]]''. Contemporary critics praised its fashion and theatricals and grossed over US$62.7&nbsp;million (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|62.7|r=2|1990}}}} million in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars{{inflation-fn|US}}) from 57 concerts.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Beck |first1=John |title=Sticker Shock : Astronomically Outpacing Inflation, Concert Ticket Costs Continue Upward, But Fans Continue To Pay The Price|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SA&p_theme=sa&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0FD2C92A52378288&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |website=[[The Press Democrat]] |accessdate=September 15, 2019 |date=August 24, 2003|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Bruenger|2016|pp=186}}</ref> It was subject to controversy due to its sexual and catholic imagery. In Italy, a private association of Roman Catholics called for a boycott of the shows in Rome and Turin; [[Pope John Paul II]] urged the general public and the Christian community not to attend the tour.<ref name=bbc>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/5006008.stm|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=May 23, 2006|last=Grunt|first=Gary|title=Madonna's giant cross offensive|accessdate=December 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Michaels |first1=Sean |title=Madonna dedicates \"Like a Virgin\" to the Pope |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/sep/08/madonna.dedicates.song.pope |work=The Guardian |accessdate=September 15, 2019 |date=September 8, 2008}}</ref> During the first show in Toronto, on May 27, local police threatened to arrest Madonna for \"lewd and indecent display\", specifically the masturbation scene during the performance of \"[[Like a Virgin (song)|Like a Virgin]]\".<ref name=\"BB25\">{{cite web |last1=Lynch |first1=Joe |title=Madonna Was Nearly Arrested for Simulating Masturbation 25 Years Ago Today |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6582939/madonna-masturbation-like-a-virgin-controversy-toronto-anniversary |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=September 15, 2019 |date=May 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn May 1990, Jonathan Takiff from ''[[The Pittsburgh Press]]'' reported that the first Japanese shows from the tour were recorded and set to be released on [[Laserdisc]] by [[Pioneer Corporation|Pioneer Artists]], one of the tour's main sponsors.<ref name=Takiff>{{cite web |last1=Takiff |first1=Jonathan |title=Madonna's new tour challenges competitors |url=https://books.google.com.mx/books?id=jt8cAAAAIBAJ&lpg=PA1&hl=es&pg=PA27#v=onepage&q&f=false |work=[[The Pittsburgh Press]] |accessdate=7 April 2020 |page=27 |date=May 9, 1990}}</ref> Takiff also reported that the final show on [[Nice]], [[France]] would be broadcast on [[MTV]].<ref name=Takiff/> Two months later, [[HBO]] confirmed they had signed on Madonna and would broadcast the tour's final show in what would be her first television special.<ref name=\"Spokane\">{{cite news |last1=Shister |first1=Gail |title=HBO signs on Madonna! |url=https://books.google.com.mx/books?id=GbYSAAAAIBAJ&lpg=PA1&hl=es&pg=PA11#v=onepage&q&f=false |work=[[Spokane Daily Chronicle]] |publisher=[[Knight Ridder]] |date=July 2, 1990}}</ref> HBO spokesperson Betty Bitterman stated that \"it's a very hot item that attracted all major players. We're not concerned about any negative feedback. We decided to do the show and that was that\".<ref name=\"Spokane\"/> When asked if the network would censor the singer's \"lewd\" behavior, Bitterman responded that \"if she's doing it, the audience will see it. We're not editing anything out. [...] We want it to feel live - as if you were there\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moca |first1=Diane Joy |title=It's ''that'' Blond on HBO |url=https://books.google.com.mx/books?id=RENWAAAAIBAJ&lpg=PA1&hl=es&pg=PA38#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=Los Angeles Times |publisher=[[The Register-Guard]] |date=August 5, 1990}}</ref>  It was not a [[pay-per-view]] special as the channel wanted to distinguish itself from its pay-TV rival, [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]], and was predicted to be HBO's highest rated special since [[Mike Tyson]] and [[Frank Bruno]]'s heavyweight fight, which aired on February 1989.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Miller |first1=Ron |title=Live Madonna show suggests HBO's own 'Blond Ambition' |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1990-08-04-9003050460-story.html |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |accessdate=September 16, 2019 |date=August 4, 1990}}</ref><ref name=\"Spokane\"/> Advertised as \"America's No.{{nbsp}}1 female pop star in a live-by-satellite performance of one of the summer's biggest pop music events\", ''Live! Madonna: Blond Ambition World Tour 90'' aired on Sunday August 5, 1990 at 9 p.m and gave HBO a record for the highest ratings ever for an entertainment special at the time; around 4,5 million people tuned in.<ref name=\"tarap\">{{harvnb|Taraborrelli|2002|p=172}}</ref>\n\n== Release and reception ==\n[[File:LIkeAPrayerBlondAmbitionUnderGround.jpg|thumb|The performance of \"[[Like a Prayer (song)|Like a Prayer]]\" was praised by ''Entertainment Weekly''{{'}}s Ty Burr]]\nThe special was released exclusively on Laserdisc under the title ''Blond Ambition World Tour Live'' on December 13, 1990. Steven Galloway, president of Pioneer Artists, said that the exclusive grew when the company signed up to sponsor the tour; they also wanted to use the singer to increase Laserdisc sales and reach a demographic of 18\u201335 year olds.<ref name=\"Pioneer\">{{cite web |last1=Hilburn |first1=Robert |title=Pioneer Has Ambitions for Madonna Concert Disc |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1990-12-15-ca-5774-story.html |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=7 April 2020 |date=December 15, 1889}}</ref> ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' called this \"the marketing coup of the year\".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=McGowan |first1=Chris |title=1990 in review: Laser scans |journal=Billboard |date=December 22, 1990 |volume=102 |issue=51 |page=68 |url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/90s/1990/Billboard-1990-12-22.pdf#page=122 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |format=PDF |issn=0006-2510}}</ref> Laserdisc sales were reported to have increased 285%; due to the overwhelmingly strong sales, it was not released on [[VHS]] until the end of 1991.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Thanks to the miracle of Laserdisc, she's a virgin all over again |journal=Billboard |date=December 22, 1990 |volume=102 |issue=51 |page=65 |url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/90s/1990/Billboard-1990-12-22.pdf#page=119 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |format=PDF |issn=0006-2510}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=McGowan |first1=Chris |title=A special focus: Laserdisc - The most versatile audio/video source for entertainment and information in the '90s comes sharply into view |journal=Billboard |date=January 12, 1991 |volume=103 |issue=2 |page=42 |url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/90s/1991/BB-1991-01-12.pdf#page=58 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |format=PDF |issn=0006-2510}}</ref> Although Madonna's then manager Caresse Henry said in 2002 that a DVD was on the works, no release date was ever given.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Caulfield |first1=Keith |title=News on Madonna, 'Krush Groove,' Zero 7 |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/73510/billboard-bits-madonna-krush-groove-zero-7 |work=Billboard |accessdate=7 April 2020 |date=August 11, 2002}}</ref> In addition to HBO, other concerts from the tour were also recorded and broadcast; one of the Yokohama dates was recorded and released exclusively in Japan under the title ''Blond Ambition - Japan Tour 90''.<ref name=\"yokohama\">{{cite video|people=Madonna|title=Blond Ambition \u2013 Japan Tour 90|medium=VHS|publisher=Warner-Pioneer Japan|date=1990}}</ref> Spanish broadcaster [[Televisi\u00f3n Espa\u00f1ola|TVE]] aired the concert in Barcelona in 30 countries.<ref name=\"Calderon\">{{cite web |last1=Fern\u00e1ndez Rubio |first1=Andr\u00e9s |title=Madonna convoco a 50.000 personas en Madrid |url=https://elpais.com/diario/1990/07/28/cultura/649116005_850215.html |work=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |accessdate=September 15, 2019 |language=Spanish |date=July 28, 1990}}</ref> One of the shows at London's [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]] was broadcast on [[BBC Radio 1]], which led to controversy over the [[profanity]] Madonna used live on air.<ref name=\"showstealer\">{{cite news|first=Neil |last=Smith|date=May 24, 2004|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3704915.stm |publisher=BBC|title=Show Stealer Madonna on Tour|accessdate=September 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Ty Burr]], from ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', gave the release an A and felt that it captured the Blond Ambition show better than ''[[Madonna: Truth or Dare]]''; \"the show itself works much better [...] Because it's a laserdisc with digital sound, the music is re-created with startling fidelity. You get this two-hour spectacle as it was meant to be: uninterrupted and over the top\".<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite web |last1=Burr |first1=Ty |title=Madonna Blond Ambition World Tour Live |url=https://ew.com/article/1991/10/04/madonna-blond-ambition-world-tour-live/ |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=7 April 2020 |date=October 4, 1991}}</ref> Burr also praised the \"gymnastic dance productions\" of numbers such as \"Where's the Party\" and \"[[Like a Prayer (song)|Like a Prayer]]\".<ref name=\"EW\"/> ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''{{'}} Robert Willburn felt that \"the new, edited laser version offers much more of the vitality and charm of the show itself than the HBO special\".<ref name=\"Pioneer\"/> [[Allmusic]] gave a rating of three out of five stars.<ref>{{cite web |title=Blond Ambition World Tour: Live  > Overview |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/blond-ambition-world-tour-live-mw0001880231 |publisher=[[Allmusic]]. [[Rovi Corporation]] |accessdate=7 April 2020 |date=July 1, 1991}}</ref> Negative criticism came from the ''Los Angeles Times'', who opined that the reason the show didn't work as a television experience was that it was \"less a concert than an unfolding passion play\" that \"rendered ponderous by distracting camera angles\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Madonna on HBO fell flat |url=https://books.google.com.mx/books?id=YHs1AAAAIBAJ&lpg=PA1&hl=es&pg=PA13#v=onepage&q&f=false |work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Reading Eagle]] |accessdate=7 April 2020 |page=13 |date=August 7, 1990}}</ref> ''Blond Ambition World Tour Live'' earned Madonna her very first [[Grammy]] win for [[Best Long Form Music Video]] at the [[34th Grammy Awards|34th ceremony]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Grammy Awards - Madonna |url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/madonna |publisher=[[The Recording Academy]] |accessdate=September 16, 2019}}</ref> ''Blond Ambition World Tour Live'' reached the second position of the Top Laserdisc Sales chart in the United States.<ref name=\"lucy1\">{{harvnb|O'Brien|2008|p=231}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed     = \n| headline      = Side one\n| extra_column  = \n| total_length  = 57:50\n\n| title1        = [[Express Yourself (Madonna song)|Express Yourself]]\n| writer1       = {{hlist|[[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]|[[Stephen Bray]]}}\n| length1       = 7:53\n\n| title2        = [[Open Your Heart (Madonna song)|Open Your Heart]]\n| writer2       = {{hlist|Madonna|[[Gardner Cole]]|Peter Rafelson}}\n| length2       = 4:33\n\n| title3        = [[Causing a Commotion]]\n| writer3       = {{hlist|Madonna|Bray}}\n| length3       = 4:10\n\n| title4        = Where's the Party\n| writer4       = {{hlist|Madonna|Bray|[[Patrick Leonard]]}}\n| length4       = 5:18\n\n| title5        = [[Like a Virgin (song)|Like a Virgin]]\n| writer5       = {{hlist|[[Tom Kelly (musician)|Tom Kelly]]|[[Billy Steinberg]]}}\n| length5       = 5:10\n\n| title6        = [[Like a Prayer (song)|Like a Prayer]]\n| writer6       = {{hlist|Madonna|Leonard}}\n| length6       = 7:47\n\n| title7        = [[Live to Tell]]\" / \"[[Oh Father]]\n| writer7      = {{hlist|Madonna|Leonard}}\n| length7       = 5:51\n\n| title8        = [[Papa Don't Preach]]\n| writer8       = {{hlist|Madonna|Brian Elliot}}\n| length8       = 4:46\n\n| title9        = [[Sooner or Later (Madonna song)|Sooner or Later]]\n| writer9       = [[Stephen Sondheim]]\n| length9       = 3:33\n\n| title10       = [[Hanky Panky (Madonna song)|Hanky Panky]]\n| writer10      = {{hlist|Madonna|Leonard}}\n| length10      = 3:56\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed     = \n| headline      = Side two\n| extra_column  = \n| total_length  = 54:10\n\n| title1       = Now I'm Following You\n| writer1      = {{hlist|[[Andy Paley]]|Jeff Lass|Ned Claflin|Jonathan Paley}}\n| length1      = 7:09\n\n| title2       = [[Material Girl]]\n| writer2      = {{hlist|[[Peter Brown (singer)|Peter Brown]]|Robert Rans}}\n| length2      = 4:35\n\n| title3       = [[Cherish (Madonna song)|Cherish]]\n| writer3      = {{hlist|Madonna|Leonard}}\n| length3      = 6:45\n\n| title4       = [[Into the Groove]]\n| writer4      = {{hlist|Madonna|Bray}}\n| length4      = 8:11\n\n| title5       = [[Vogue (Madonna song)|Vogue]]\n| writer5      = {{hlist|Madonna|[[Shep Pettibone]]}}\n| length5      = 7:48\n\n| title6       = [[Holiday (Madonna song)|Holiday]]\n| writer6      = {{hlist|[[Pure Energy (group)|Curtis Hudson]]|Lisa Stevens}}\n| length6      = 7:22\n\n| title7       = [[Family Affair (Sly and the Family Stone song)|Family Affair]]\n| writer7      = [[Sly Stone]]\n| length7      = 2:33\n\n| title8       = [[Keep It Together (Madonna song)|Keep It Together]]\n| writer8      = {{hlist|Madonna|Bray}}\n| length8      = 13:06\n\n}}\n\n'''Notes'''<ref name=\"Liners\"/>\n*\"Express Yourself\" contains an excerpt from \"[[Everybody (Madonna song)|Everybody]].\"\n*\"Like a Prayer\" contains an excerpt from \"Act of Contrition\".\n*\"Into the Groove\" contains an excerpt from \"[[Ain't Nobody Better]]\".\n*\"Holiday\" contains an excerpt from \"Do the Bus Stop\".\n\n==Credits and personnel==\n* [[David Mallet (director)|David Mallet]] \u2013 [[Film director|director]]\n* Anthony Eaton \u2013 producer\n* Freddy De Mann \u2013 [[Film producer|executive producer]]\n* Christopher Ciccone \u2013 [[art direction]]\n* Vince Patterson \u2013 [[choreographer]]\n* Kevin Alexander Stea \u2013 assistant choreographer\n\nCredits per the notes of ''Blond Ambition World Tour Live''<ref name=\"Liners\">{{cite video|people=Madonna|title=Blond Ambition World Tour Live|medium=Laserdisc|publisher=Pioneer Artists|date=1990}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n*{{Cite book|last=Taraborrelli|first=J. Randy|title=[[Madonna: An Intimate Biography]]|authorlink=J. Randy Taraborrelli|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|year=2002|isbn=978-0-4251-8669-5|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|last=O'Brien|first=Lucy|title=[[Madonna: Like an Icon]]|year=2008|authorlink=Lucy O'Brien|publisher=[[Bantam Press]]|isbn=0-593-05547-0}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{imdb title|0100089}}\n\n{{Madonna}}\n\n[[Category:1990 video albums]]\n[[Category:Concert films]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award for Best Long Form Music Video]]\n[[Category:LaserDisc releases]]\n[[Category:Live video albums]]\n[[Category:Madonna (entertainer) video albums]]\n[[Category:Sire Records video albums]]\n[[Category:Warner Records video albums]]\n[[Category:HBO network specials]]\n[[Category:1990 television specials]]\n[[Category:Films directed by David Mallet (director)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Blond Ambition World Tour Live\n| type       = video\n| artist     = [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]\n| cover      = Madonna - Blond Ambition Live (Laser disc).png\n| alt        =\n| released   = December 13, 1990\n| recorded   = August 5, 1990\n| venue      = [[Stade Charles-Ehrmann|Stade de l'Ouest]]<br />([[Nice|Nice, France]])\n| studio     =\n| length     = 112 mins\n| label      = [[Pioneer Corporation|Pioneer Artists]]\n| director   = [[David Mallet (director)|David Mallet]]\n| producer   = Anthony Eaton\n| chronology = [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] video\n| prev_title = [[The Immaculate Collection (video)|The Immaculate Collection]]\n| prev_year  = 1990\n| next_title = [[The Girlie Show - Live Down Under]]\n| next_year  = 1994\n}}\n\n'''''Blond Ambition World Tour Live'''''  is a video album by American singer-songwriter [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] released exclusively on [[Laserdisc]] by [[Pioneer Corporation|Pioneer Artists]] on December 13, 1990. It contained the [[Blond Ambition World Tour]]'s final show, filmed at the [[Stade Charles-Ehrmann|Stade de l'Ouest]] in [[Nice|Nice, France]] on August 5, 1990. The concert had previously been broadcast on American network [[HBO]] as ''Live! Madonna: Blond Ambition World Tour 90'', and became one of its highest rated specials. The decision to release it exclusively on Laserdisc grew when Pioneer Artists signed up to sponsor the tour; the company also wanted to use Madonna to reach a new demographic and increase Laserdisc sales. It received positive reviews, with some critics saying it captured the concert better than the documentary ''[[Madonna: Truth or Dare]]'' and the HBO broadcast. At the [[34th Annual Grammy Awards]], it won for [[Grammy Award for Best Music Film|Best Music Video-Long Form]], becoming the first Grammy award Madonna received in her career.\n\n== Background ==\nThe Blond Ambition World Tour was Madonna's third concert tour. It supported her fourth studio album ''[[Like a Prayer (album)|Like a Prayer]]'' and the ''[[Dick Tracy (1990 film)|Dick Tracy]]'' soundtrack ''[[I'm Breathless]]''. Contemporary critics praised its fashion and theatricals and grossed over US$62.7&nbsp;million (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|62.7|r=2|1990}}}} million in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars{{inflation-fn|US}}) from 57 concerts.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Beck |first1=John |title=Sticker Shock : Astronomically Outpacing Inflation, Concert Ticket Costs Continue Upward, But Fans Continue To Pay The Price|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SA&p_theme=sa&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0FD2C92A52378288&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |website=[[The Press Democrat]] |accessdate=September 15, 2019 |date=August 24, 2003|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Bruenger|2016|pp=186}}</ref> It was subject to controversy due to its sexual and catholic imagery. In Italy, a private association of Roman Catholics called for a boycott of the shows in Rome and Turin; [[Pope John Paul II]] urged the general public and the Christian community not to attend the tour.<ref name=bbc>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/5006008.stm|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=May 23, 2006|last=Grunt|first=Gary|title=Madonna's giant cross offensive|accessdate=December 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Michaels |first1=Sean |title=Madonna dedicates \"Like a Virgin\" to the Pope |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/sep/08/madonna.dedicates.song.pope |work=The Guardian |accessdate=September 15, 2019 |date=September 8, 2008}}</ref> During the first show in Toronto, on May 27, local police threatened to arrest Madonna for \"lewd and indecent display\", specifically the masturbation scene during the performance of \"[[Like a Virgin (song)|Like a Virgin]]\".<ref name=\"BB25\">{{cite web |last1=Lynch |first1=Joe |title=Madonna Was Nearly Arrested for Simulating Masturbation 25 Years Ago Today |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6582939/madonna-masturbation-like-a-virgin-controversy-toronto-anniversary |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=September 15, 2019 |date=May 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn May 1990, Jonathan Takiff from ''[[The Pittsburgh Press]]'' reported that the first Japanese shows from the tour were recorded and set to be released on [[Laserdisc]] by [[Pioneer Corporation|Pioneer Artists]], one of the tour's main sponsors.<ref name=Takiff>{{cite web |last1=Takiff |first1=Jonathan |title=Madonna's new tour challenges competitors |url=https://books.google.com.mx/books?id=jt8cAAAAIBAJ&lpg=PA1&hl=es&pg=PA27#v=onepage&q&f=false |work=[[The Pittsburgh Press]] |accessdate=7 April 2020 |page=27 |date=May 9, 1990}}</ref> Takiff also reported that the final show on [[Nice]], [[France]] would be broadcast on [[MTV]].<ref name=Takiff/> Two months later, [[HBO]] confirmed they had signed on Madonna and would broadcast the tour's final show in what would be her first television special.<ref name=\"Spokane\">{{cite news |last1=Shister |first1=Gail |title=HBO signs on Madonna! |url=https://books.google.com.mx/books?id=GbYSAAAAIBAJ&lpg=PA1&hl=es&pg=PA11#v=onepage&q&f=false |work=[[Spokane Daily Chronicle]] |publisher=[[Knight Ridder]] |date=July 2, 1990}}</ref> HBO spokesperson Betty Bitterman stated that \"it's a very hot item that attracted all major players. We're not concerned about any negative feedback. We decided to do the show and that was that\".<ref name=\"Spokane\"/> When asked if the network would censor the singer's \"lewd\" behavior, Bitterman responded that \"if she's doing it, the audience will see it. We're not editing anything out. [...] We want it to feel live - as if you were there\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moca |first1=Diane Joy |title=It's ''that'' Blond on HBO |url=https://books.google.com.mx/books?id=RENWAAAAIBAJ&lpg=PA1&hl=es&pg=PA38#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=Los Angeles Times |publisher=[[The Register-Guard]] |date=August 5, 1990}}</ref>  It was not a [[pay-per-view]] special as the channel wanted to distinguish itself from its pay-TV rival, [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]], and was predicted to be HBO's highest rated special since [[Mike Tyson]] and [[Frank Bruno]]'s heavyweight fight, which aired on February 1989.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Miller |first1=Ron |title=Live Madonna show suggests HBO's own 'Blond Ambition' |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1990-08-04-9003050460-story.html |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |accessdate=September 16, 2019 |date=August 4, 1990}}</ref><ref name=\"Spokane\"/> Advertised as \"America's No.{{nbsp}}1 female pop star in a live-by-satellite performance of one of the summer's biggest pop music events\", ''Live! Madonna: Blond Ambition World Tour 90'' aired on Sunday August 5, 1990 at 9 p.m and gave HBO a record for the highest ratings ever for an entertainment special at the time; around 4,5 million people tuned in.<ref name=\"tarap\">{{harvnb|Taraborrelli|2002|p=172}}</ref>\n\n== Release and reception ==\n[[File:LIkeAPrayerBlondAmbitionUnderGround.jpg|thumb|The performance of \"[[Like a Prayer (song)|Like a Prayer]]\" was praised by ''Entertainment Weekly''{{'}}s Ty Burr]]\nThe special was released exclusively on Laserdisc under the title ''Blond Ambition World Tour Live'' on December 13, 1990. Steven Galloway, president of Pioneer Artists, said that the exclusive grew when the company signed up to sponsor the tour; they also wanted to use the singer to increase Laserdisc sales and reach a demographic of 18\u201335 year olds.<ref name=\"Pioneer\">{{cite web |last1=Hilburn |first1=Robert |title=Pioneer Has Ambitions for Madonna Concert Disc |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1990-12-15-ca-5774-story.html |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=7 April 2020 |date=December 15, 1990}}</ref> ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' called this \"the marketing coup of the year\".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=McGowan |first1=Chris |title=1990 in review: Laser scans |journal=Billboard |date=December 22, 1990 |volume=102 |issue=51 |page=68 |url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/90s/1990/Billboard-1990-12-22.pdf#page=122 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |format=PDF |issn=0006-2510}}</ref> Laserdisc sales were reported to have increased 285%; due to the overwhelmingly strong sales, it was not released on [[VHS]] until the end of 1991.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Thanks to the miracle of Laserdisc, she's a virgin all over again |journal=Billboard |date=December 22, 1990 |volume=102 |issue=51 |page=65 |url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/90s/1990/Billboard-1990-12-22.pdf#page=119 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |format=PDF |issn=0006-2510}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=McGowan |first1=Chris |title=A special focus: Laserdisc - The most versatile audio/video source for entertainment and information in the '90s comes sharply into view |journal=Billboard |date=January 12, 1991 |volume=103 |issue=2 |page=42 |url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/90s/1991/BB-1991-01-12.pdf#page=58 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |format=PDF |issn=0006-2510}}</ref> Although Madonna's then manager Caresse Henry said in 2002 that a DVD was on the works, no release date was ever given.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Caulfield |first1=Keith |title=News on Madonna, 'Krush Groove,' Zero 7 |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/73510/billboard-bits-madonna-krush-groove-zero-7 |work=Billboard |accessdate=7 April 2020 |date=August 11, 2002}}</ref> In addition to HBO, other concerts from the tour were also recorded and broadcast; one of the Yokohama dates was recorded and released exclusively in Japan under the title ''Blond Ambition - Japan Tour 90''.<ref name=\"yokohama\">{{cite video|people=Madonna|title=Blond Ambition \u2013 Japan Tour 90|medium=VHS|publisher=Warner-Pioneer Japan|date=1990}}</ref> Spanish broadcaster [[Televisi\u00f3n Espa\u00f1ola|TVE]] aired the concert in Barcelona in 30 countries.<ref name=\"Calderon\">{{cite web |last1=Fern\u00e1ndez Rubio |first1=Andr\u00e9s |title=Madonna convoco a 50.000 personas en Madrid |url=https://elpais.com/diario/1990/07/28/cultura/649116005_850215.html |work=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |accessdate=September 15, 2019 |language=Spanish |date=July 28, 1990}}</ref> One of the shows at London's [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]] was broadcast on [[BBC Radio 1]], which led to controversy over the [[profanity]] Madonna used live on air.<ref name=\"showstealer\">{{cite news|first=Neil |last=Smith|date=May 24, 2004|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3704915.stm |publisher=BBC|title=Show Stealer Madonna on Tour|accessdate=September 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Ty Burr]], from ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', gave the release an A and felt that it captured the Blond Ambition show better than ''[[Madonna: Truth or Dare]]''; \"the show itself works much better [...] Because it's a laserdisc with digital sound, the music is re-created with startling fidelity. You get this two-hour spectacle as it was meant to be: uninterrupted and over the top\".<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite web |last1=Burr |first1=Ty |title=Madonna Blond Ambition World Tour Live |url=https://ew.com/article/1991/10/04/madonna-blond-ambition-world-tour-live/ |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=7 April 2020 |date=October 4, 1991}}</ref> Burr also praised the \"gymnastic dance productions\" of numbers such as \"Where's the Party\" and \"[[Like a Prayer (song)|Like a Prayer]]\".<ref name=\"EW\"/> ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''{{'}} Robert Willburn felt that \"the new, edited laser version offers much more of the vitality and charm of the show itself than the HBO special\".<ref name=\"Pioneer\"/> [[Allmusic]] gave a rating of three out of five stars.<ref>{{cite web |title=Blond Ambition World Tour: Live  > Overview |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/blond-ambition-world-tour-live-mw0001880231 |publisher=[[Allmusic]]. [[Rovi Corporation]] |accessdate=7 April 2020 |date=July 1, 1991}}</ref> Negative criticism came from the ''Los Angeles Times'', who opined that the reason the show didn't work as a television experience was that it was \"less a concert than an unfolding passion play\" that \"rendered ponderous by distracting camera angles\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Madonna on HBO fell flat |url=https://books.google.com.mx/books?id=YHs1AAAAIBAJ&lpg=PA1&hl=es&pg=PA13#v=onepage&q&f=false |work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Reading Eagle]] |accessdate=7 April 2020 |page=13 |date=August 7, 1990}}</ref> ''Blond Ambition World Tour Live'' earned Madonna her very first [[Grammy]] win for [[Best Long Form Music Video]] at the [[34th Grammy Awards|34th ceremony]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Grammy Awards - Madonna |url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/madonna |publisher=[[The Recording Academy]] |accessdate=September 16, 2019}}</ref> ''Blond Ambition World Tour Live'' reached the second position of the Top Laserdisc Sales chart in the United States.<ref name=\"lucy1\">{{harvnb|O'Brien|2008|p=231}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed     = \n| headline      = Side one\n| extra_column  = \n| total_length  = 57:50\n\n| title1        = [[Express Yourself (Madonna song)|Express Yourself]]\n| writer1       = {{hlist|[[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]|[[Stephen Bray]]}}\n| length1       = 7:53\n\n| title2        = [[Open Your Heart (Madonna song)|Open Your Heart]]\n| writer2       = {{hlist|Madonna|[[Gardner Cole]]|Peter Rafelson}}\n| length2       = 4:33\n\n| title3        = [[Causing a Commotion]]\n| writer3       = {{hlist|Madonna|Bray}}\n| length3       = 4:10\n\n| title4        = Where's the Party\n| writer4       = {{hlist|Madonna|Bray|[[Patrick Leonard]]}}\n| length4       = 5:18\n\n| title5        = [[Like a Virgin (song)|Like a Virgin]]\n| writer5       = {{hlist|[[Tom Kelly (musician)|Tom Kelly]]|[[Billy Steinberg]]}}\n| length5       = 5:10\n\n| title6        = [[Like a Prayer (song)|Like a Prayer]]\n| writer6       = {{hlist|Madonna|Leonard}}\n| length6       = 7:47\n\n| title7        = [[Live to Tell]]\" / \"[[Oh Father]]\n| writer7      = {{hlist|Madonna|Leonard}}\n| length7       = 5:51\n\n| title8        = [[Papa Don't Preach]]\n| writer8       = {{hlist|Madonna|Brian Elliot}}\n| length8       = 4:46\n\n| title9        = [[Sooner or Later (Madonna song)|Sooner or Later]]\n| writer9       = [[Stephen Sondheim]]\n| length9       = 3:33\n\n| title10       = [[Hanky Panky (Madonna song)|Hanky Panky]]\n| writer10      = {{hlist|Madonna|Leonard}}\n| length10      = 3:56\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed     = \n| headline      = Side two\n| extra_column  = \n| total_length  = 54:10\n\n| title1       = Now I'm Following You\n| writer1      = {{hlist|[[Andy Paley]]|Jeff Lass|Ned Claflin|Jonathan Paley}}\n| length1      = 7:09\n\n| title2       = [[Material Girl]]\n| writer2      = {{hlist|[[Peter Brown (singer)|Peter Brown]]|Robert Rans}}\n| length2      = 4:35\n\n| title3       = [[Cherish (Madonna song)|Cherish]]\n| writer3      = {{hlist|Madonna|Leonard}}\n| length3      = 6:45\n\n| title4       = [[Into the Groove]]\n| writer4      = {{hlist|Madonna|Bray}}\n| length4      = 8:11\n\n| title5       = [[Vogue (Madonna song)|Vogue]]\n| writer5      = {{hlist|Madonna|[[Shep Pettibone]]}}\n| length5      = 7:48\n\n| title6       = [[Holiday (Madonna song)|Holiday]]\n| writer6      = {{hlist|[[Pure Energy (group)|Curtis Hudson]]|Lisa Stevens}}\n| length6      = 7:22\n\n| title7       = [[Family Affair (Sly and the Family Stone song)|Family Affair]]\n| writer7      = [[Sly Stone]]\n| length7      = 2:33\n\n| title8       = [[Keep It Together (Madonna song)|Keep It Together]]\n| writer8      = {{hlist|Madonna|Bray}}\n| length8      = 13:06\n\n}}\n\n'''Notes'''<ref name=\"Liners\"/>\n*\"Express Yourself\" contains an excerpt from \"[[Everybody (Madonna song)|Everybody]].\"\n*\"Like a Prayer\" contains an excerpt from \"Act of Contrition\".\n*\"Into the Groove\" contains an excerpt from \"[[Ain't Nobody Better]]\".\n*\"Holiday\" contains an excerpt from \"Do the Bus Stop\".\n\n==Credits and personnel==\n* [[David Mallet (director)|David Mallet]] \u2013 [[Film director|director]]\n* Anthony 